288
00:22:58,706 --> 00:23:03,585
Hadley busted his head up pretty good.
The doc had already gone home for the night.

289
00:23:03,886 --> 00:23:06,421
Poor bastard lay there till this morning.

290
00:23:06,422 --> 00:23:09,237
By then, hell, there weren't
nothing we could do.

291
00:23:15,056 --> 00:23:17,020
What was his name?

292
00:23:19,894 --> 00:23:21,649
What did you say?

293
00:23:23,147 --> 00:23:25,607
I was just wondering if
anyone knew his name.

294
00:23:26,408 --> 00:23:28,698
What the fuck do you care, new fish?

295
00:23:29,779 --> 00:23:33,036
It doesn't fuckin' matter what
his name was. He's dead.

296
00:23:52,510 --> 00:23:53,628
Hey...

297
00:23:54,929 --> 00:23:57,161
Anybody come at you yet?

298
00:23:59,183 --> 00:24:01,564
Anybody get to you yet?

299
00:24:02,811 --> 00:24:05,439
Hey, we all need friends in here.

300
00:24:05,740 --> 00:24:07,437
I could be a friend to you.

301
00:24:10,419 --> 00:24:11,666
Hey...

302
00:24:16,325 --> 00:24:18,081
Hard to get.

303
00:24:19,871 --> 00:24:21,418
I like that.

304
00:24:28,171 --> 00:24:31,548
<i>Andy kept pretty
much to himself at first.</i>

305
00:24:31,949 --> 00:24:36,983
<i>I guess he had a lot on his mind,
trying to adapt to life on the inside.</i>

306
00:24:37,847 --> 00:24:40,740
<i>It wasn't until a month went by
that he opened his mouth...</i>

307
00:24:40,741 --> 00:24:43,314
<i>to say more than two words to somebody.</i>

308
00:24:44,854 --> 00:24:48,779
<i>As it turned out...
that somebody was me.</i>

309
00:24:52,287 --> 00:24:55,636
<i>Officers Russell and Burwell
report to the duty officer.</i>

310
00:24:57,700 --> 00:24:59,535
I'm Andy Dufresne.

311
00:25:00,536 --> 00:25:02,501
The wife-killing banker.

312
00:25:04,657 --> 00:25:05,749
Why did you do it?

313
00:25:06,450 --> 00:25:07,959
I didn't, since you ask.

314
00:25:07,960 --> 00:25:10,588
You're gonna fit right in!

315
00:25:11,089 --> 00:25:13,541
Everybody in here's innocent.
Didn't you know that?

316
00:25:14,142 --> 00:25:17,657
- Heywood, what are you in here for?
- Didn't do it. Lawyer fucked me.

317
00:25:20,798 --> 00:25:22,975
Rumor has it you're a real cold fish.

318
00:25:23,376 --> 00:25:26,812
You think your shit smells
sweeter than most. Is that right?

319
00:25:27,313 --> 00:25:30,231
- What do you think?
- To tell you the truth,

320
00:25:30,332 --> 00:25:32,901
I haven't made up my mind.

321
00:25:33,102 --> 00:25:35,972
I understand you're a man
that knows how to get things.

322
00:25:37,073 --> 00:25:40,159
I'm known to locate certain
things, from time to time.

323
00:25:40,660 --> 00:25:43,245
- I wonder if you might get me
a rock hammer. - A what?

324
00:25:43,746 --> 00:25:45,205
A rock hammer.

325
00:25:45,706 --> 00:25:47,879
- What is it, and why?
- What do you care?

326
00:25:49,377 --> 00:25:52,437
Well, if it was a toothbrush, I wouldn't
a question, I'd just quote a price,

327
00:25:52,438 --> 00:25:55,103
but then a toothbrush is
a non-lethal object, isn't it?

328
00:25:56,342 --> 00:25:57,535
Fair enough.

329
00:25:58,136 --> 00:26:00,879
A rock hammer is about
six or seven inches long.

330
00:26:01,130 --> 00:26:03,398
- Looks like a miniature pickax.
- Pickax?

331
00:26:03,399 --> 00:26:05,564
- For rocks.
- Rocks.

332
00:26:07,353 --> 00:26:08,504
Quartz?

333
00:26:09,805 --> 00:26:10,953
Quartz.

334
00:26:12,525 --> 00:26:14,585
And some mica.

335
00:26:15,186 --> 00:26:16,533
Shale.

336
00:26:17,238 --> 00:26:18,705
Limestone.

337
00:26:18,906 --> 00:26:19,807
So?

338
00:26:20,908 --> 00:26:22,576
So, I'm a rock hound.

339
00:26:23,077 --> 00:26:26,471
At least, I was in my old life.
I'd like to be again on a limited basis.

340
00:26:26,672 --> 00:26:29,082
Or maybe you want
to hammer somebody's skull.

341
00:26:29,483 --> 00:26:30,421
No, sir.

342
00:26:31,169 --> 00:26:32,836
I have no enemies here.

343
00:26:32,837 --> 00:26:35,593
No? Wait a while.

344
00:26:36,757 --> 00:26:38,109
Word gets around.

345
00:26:39,010 --> 00:26:41,320
The Sisters have taken quite a liking to you.

346
00:26:43,181 --> 00:26:44,394
Especially Bogs.

347
00:26:45,499 --> 00:26:49,394
I don't suppose it would help any
if I explained to them I'm not homosexual.

348
00:26:49,395 --> 00:26:50,979
Neither are they.

349
00:26:50,980 --> 00:26:54,070
You have to be human first.
They don't qualify.

350
00:26:59,145 --> 00:27:03,075
Bull queers take by force.
It's all they want or understand.

351
00:27:03,576 --> 00:27:06,787
If I were you, I'd grow eyes
in the back of my head.

352
00:27:07,288 --> 00:27:08,705
Thanks for the advice.

353
00:27:08,706 --> 00:27:10,073
Well, that's free.

354
00:27:10,374 --> 00:27:12,209
You understand my concern.

355
00:27:12,710 --> 00:27:16,037
Well, if there's any trouble,
I won't use the hammer, OK?

356
00:27:16,238 --> 00:27:19,929
Then I guess you want to escape.
Tunnel under the wall, maybe.

357
00:27:21,010 --> 00:27:22,886
Did I miss something? What's funny?

358
00:27:22,887 --> 00:27:25,811
You'll understand when
you see the rock hammer.

359
00:27:27,808 --> 00:27:32,521
- What's an item like this usually go for?
- Seven dollars in any rock and gem shop.

360
00:27:33,022 --> 00:27:35,232
My normal mark-up's 20 per cent.

361
00:27:35,833 --> 00:27:37,860
But this is a specialty item.

362
00:27:38,361 --> 00:27:40,445
The risk goes up, the price goes up.

363
00:27:40,947 --> 00:27:42,989
Let's make it an even ten bucks.

364
00:27:43,090 --> 00:27:44,045
Ten it is.

365
00:27:45,952 --> 00:27:47,753
Waste of money, if you ask me.

366
00:27:48,454 --> 00:27:49,376
Why's that?

367
00:27:51,082 --> 00:27:54,005
Folks around this joint
love surprise inspections.

368
00:27:55,711 --> 00:27:57,288
If they find it, you're gonna lose it.

369
00:27:58,089 --> 00:28:00,098
If they do catch you with it,
you don't know me.

370
00:28:00,499 --> 00:28:02,892
You mention my name, we
never do business again.

371
00:28:03,193 --> 00:28:05,600
Not for shoelaces or a stick of gum.
Now, you got that?

372
00:28:07,223 --> 00:28:08,223
I understand.

373
00:28:09,724 --> 00:28:10,141
Thank you...

374
00:28:11,142 --> 00:28:12,251
Mr. er...?

375
00:28:12,252 --> 00:28:15,438
- Red. The name's Red.
- Red?

376
00:28:16,439 --> 00:28:18,171
Why do they call you that?

377
00:28:21,862 --> 00:28:23,827
Maybe it's because I'm Irish.

378
00:28:31,914 --> 00:28:35,041
<i>I could see why some of
the boys took him for snobby.</i>

379
00:28:35,842 --> 00:28:38,045
<i>He had a quiet way about him.</i>

380
00:28:38,546 --> 00:28:42,691
<i>A walk and a talk, that just
wasn't normal around here.</i>

381
00:28:43,092 --> 00:28:44,218
<i>He strolled...</i>

382
00:28:44,719 --> 00:28:48,639
<i>like a man in a park, without
a care or worry in the world.</i>

383
00:28:49,140 --> 00:28:53,635
<i>Like he had on an invisible coat
that would shield him from this place.</i>

384
00:28:54,136 --> 00:28:58,106
<i>Yeah. I think it would be fair to say...</i>

385
00:28:58,307 --> 00:29:00,071
<i>I liked Andy from the start.</i>

386
00:29:01,944 --> 00:29:05,535
Let's go!
Some of us have got a schedule to keep.

387
00:29:09,381 --> 00:29:11,415
Move it! Come on. Move it!

388
00:29:14,165 --> 00:29:17,672
Bob, how are you doing?
How's the wife treating you?

389
00:29:27,011 --> 00:29:28,353
Easy.

390
00:29:28,954 --> 00:29:30,518
Keep it moving.

391
00:29:34,134 --> 00:29:35,064
Red...

392
00:29:55,206 --> 00:29:59,201
<i>Andy was right.
I finally got the joke.</i>

393
00:29:59,702 --> 00:30:04,385
<i>It would take a man about 600 years
to tunnel under the wall with one of these.</i>

394
00:30:08,344 --> 00:30:10,809
- Book?
- Not today.

395
00:30:16,769 --> 00:30:18,733
- Book?
- No.

396
00:30:20,648 --> 00:30:22,236
Hey, Brooksy.

397
00:30:25,152 --> 00:30:27,617
Delivery for Dufresne.

398
00:30:34,328 --> 00:30:40,038
Book?... book?

399
00:30:42,962 --> 00:30:44,371
Dufresne...

400
00:30:45,172 --> 00:30:46,520
Here's your book.

401
00:30:51,762 --> 00:30:53,310
Thanks.

402
00:30:58,268 --> 00:31:02,627
Dufresne! We're running low on Hexlite.
Get on back and fetch us up some.

403
00:31:40,152 --> 00:31:41,895
If you get this in your eyes, it blinds you.

404
00:31:41,896 --> 00:31:45,027
Honey... hush.

405
00:31:57,102 --> 00:31:59,204
That's it. You fight.

406
00:31:59,205 --> 00:32:00,872
It's better that way.

407
00:32:09,215 --> 00:32:12,233
<i>I wish I could tell you
that Andy fought the good fight,</i>

408
00:32:12,234 --> 00:32:14,261
<i>and the Sisters let him be.</i>

409
00:32:14,762 --> 00:32:16,745
<i>I wish I could tell you that.</i>

410
00:32:17,047 --> 00:32:19,312
<i>But prison is no fairy-tale world.</i>

411
00:32:20,893 --> 00:32:22,602
<i>He never said who did it.</i>

412
00:32:23,103 --> 00:32:24,931
<i>But we all knew.</i>

413
00:32:29,485 --> 00:32:31,945
<i>Things went on like that for a while.</i>

414
00:32:32,446 --> 00:32:35,156
<i>Prison life consists of routine...</i>

415
00:32:35,157 --> 00:32:37,247
<i>and then more routine.</i>

416
00:32:39,745 --> 00:32:43,261
<i>Every so often, Andy would
show up with fresh bruises.</i>

417
00:32:44,750 --> 00:32:46,376
<i>The Sisters kept at him.</i>

418
00:32:46,877 --> 00:32:50,489
<i>Sometimes he was able to
fight 'em off. Sometimes not.</i>

419
00:32:51,990 --> 00:32:53,925
<i>And that's how it went for Andy.</i>

420
00:32:54,426 --> 00:32:56,553
<i>That was his routine.</i>

421
00:32:57,054 --> 00:33:00,632
<i>I do believe those first two
years were the worst for him.</i>

422
00:33:00,933 --> 00:33:02,308
<i>And I also believe,</i>

423
00:33:02,309 --> 00:33:06,997
<i>if things had gone on that way, this
place would have got the best of him.</i>

424
00:33:07,898 --> 00:33:13,027
<i>But then, in the spring of 1949,
the powers that be decided that...</i>

425
00:33:13,028 --> 00:33:16,031
The roof of the license-plate
factory needs resurfacing.

426
00:33:16,732 --> 00:33:19,664
I need a dozen
volunteers for a week's work.

427
00:33:20,452 --> 00:33:21,862
As you know,

428
00:33:22,363 --> 00:33:25,957
special detail carries
with it special privileges.

429
00:33:26,458 --> 00:33:28,823
<i>It was outdoor detail...</i>

430
00:33:29,345 --> 00:33:33,415
<i>...and May is one damn fine
month to be working outdoors.</i>

431
00:33:33,716 --> 00:33:35,125
Stay in line there.

432
00:33:35,726 --> 00:33:38,224
<i>More than a hundred men
volunteered for the job.</i>

433
00:33:42,725 --> 00:33:45,398
Wallace E Unger.

434
00:33:46,186 --> 00:33:48,330
Ellis Redding.

435
00:33:48,731 --> 00:33:50,349
<i>Wouldn't you know it?</i>

436
00:33:50,950 --> 00:33:54,119
<i>Me and some fellows I know
were among the names called.</i>

437
00:33:54,320 --> 00:33:56,487
<i>Andrew Dufresne.</i>

438
00:33:56,988 --> 00:33:59,516
<i>It only cost us a pack
of smokes per man.</i>

439
00:34:00,117 --> 00:34:02,910
<i>I made my usual 20 per cent, of course.</i>

440
00:34:02,911 --> 00:34:06,481
So, this big-shot lawyer
calls me long-distance from Texas.

441
00:34:06,582 --> 00:34:07,874
I say, "Yeah?"

442
00:34:08,375 --> 00:34:11,970
He says, "Sorry to inform you,
but your brother just died."

443
00:34:12,171 --> 00:34:16,515
- Oh, damn, Byron. I'm sorry to hear that.
- I'm not. He was an asshole.

444
00:34:16,616 --> 00:34:18,635
Ran off years ago.
Figured him for dead, anyway.

445
00:34:18,636 --> 00:34:22,680
So, anyway, this lawyer fella says to me,
"Your brother died a rich man."

446
00:34:22,681 --> 00:34:27,619
- Oil wells and shit. Close to a million bucks
- A million bucks?

447
00:34:28,420 --> 00:34:30,560
Fucking incredible how
lucky some assholes get.

448
00:34:30,561 --> 00:34:32,707
Jeez-Louise! Are you gonna see any of that?

449
00:34:33,108 --> 00:34:35,977
35,000. That's what he left me.

450
00:34:36,178 --> 00:34:37,779
- Dollars?
- Yeah.

451
00:34:38,280 --> 00:34:40,991
Holy shit! That's great.
That's like winning the sweepstakes.

452
00:34:41,492 --> 00:34:42,584
Isn't it?

453
00:34:43,085 --> 00:34:45,612
Dumb shit. What do you think
the government's gonna do to me?

454
00:34:45,913 --> 00:34:48,756
Take a big, wet bite out of my ass, is what.

455
00:34:49,157 --> 00:34:53,110
Poor Byron! Terrible fucking luck, huh?

456
00:34:53,111 --> 00:34:54,663
Crying shame.

457
00:34:54,964 --> 00:34:56,715
Some people really got it awful!

458
00:34:57,316 --> 00:35:01,068
Andy, are you nuts?
Keep your eyes on your mop, man. Andy!

459
00:35:01,069 --> 00:35:04,097
Well, you'll pay some tax,
but you'll still end up...

460
00:35:04,098 --> 00:35:07,216
Oh, yeah, yeah.
Maybe enough to buy a new car. Then what?

461
00:35:07,217 --> 00:35:08,977
I've got to pay tax on the car.

462
00:35:09,078 --> 00:35:13,439
Repair, maintenance, goddamn kids pestering
me to take them for a ride all the time...

463
00:35:13,440 --> 00:35:17,443
And at the end of the year, you figure the tax
wrong, you pay them out of your own pocket.

464
00:35:17,444 --> 00:35:19,396
I tell you... Uncle Sam!

465
00:35:19,697 --> 00:35:23,533
He puts his hand in your shirt
and squeezes your tit till it's purple.

466
00:35:23,534 --> 00:35:26,327
- Andy! Andy!
- What's he doing?

467
00:35:26,328 --> 00:35:28,746
- Getting himself killed.
- Keep tarring.

468
00:35:28,947 --> 00:35:31,916
Some brother! Shit.

469
00:35:31,917 --> 00:35:32,839
Hey!

470
00:35:36,296 --> 00:35:38,106
Mr. Hadley...

471
00:35:38,507 --> 00:35:40,045
do you trust your wife?

