Brooks, do you have
a piece of paper and a pencil?

712
00:54:14,522 --> 00:54:15,714
Thanks.

713
00:54:16,615 --> 00:54:18,063
So...

714
00:54:19,335 --> 00:54:21,020
Mr. Dekins...

715
00:54:21,921 --> 00:54:26,466
And then Andy says to Mr. Dekins,
"Do you want your sons to go to Harvard,

716
00:54:26,467 --> 00:54:28,677
- or Yale?"
- He didn't say that?

717
00:54:28,678 --> 00:54:31,429
As God is my witness, he did!

718
00:54:31,730 --> 00:54:35,091
Dekins just blinked for a second.
Then he laughed himself silly.

719
00:54:35,092 --> 00:54:37,352
And afterwards he shook Andy's hand.

720
00:54:37,353 --> 00:54:38,311
My ass!

721
00:54:38,312 --> 00:54:39,604
Shook his hand.

722
00:54:39,605 --> 00:54:43,149
Hell, I... I near soiled myself!

723
00:54:43,150 --> 00:54:47,445
All Andy needed was a suit and a tie
and a little jiggly hula girl on his desk,

724
00:54:47,446 --> 00:54:49,990
and he would have been:
"Mr. Dufresne, if you please"!

725
00:54:49,991 --> 00:54:52,121
Making a few friends, Andy?

726
00:54:52,785 --> 00:54:54,828
I wouldn't say "friends".

727
00:54:55,129 --> 00:54:58,715
I'm a convicted murderer who
provides sound financial planning.

728
00:54:58,716 --> 00:55:00,834
It's a wonderful pet to have.

729
00:55:01,535 --> 00:55:05,630
- Got you out of the laundry, though.
- Well, it might do more than that.

730
00:55:05,831 --> 00:55:08,717
How about expanding the library?
Get some new books in there.

731
00:55:08,718 --> 00:55:11,511
If you're gonna ask for something,
ask for a pool table.

732
00:55:12,412 --> 00:55:14,955
- Right.
- How do you expect to do that?

733
00:55:14,956 --> 00:55:19,394
I mean, get new books in here,
Mr. Dufresne, if you please?

734
00:55:19,895 --> 00:55:21,229
Ask the Warden for funds.

735
00:55:22,565 --> 00:55:26,342
Son, son, son. Six wardens have
been through here in my tenure,

736
00:55:26,343 --> 00:55:29,054
and I've learned one
immutable, universal truth.

737
00:55:29,355 --> 00:55:30,964
Not one of them born...

738
00:55:31,365 --> 00:55:33,907
whose asshole wouldn't pucker
up tighter than a snare...

739
00:55:33,908 --> 00:55:35,511
...drum when you asked them for funds.

740
00:55:37,212 --> 00:55:39,623
- The budget's stretched thin, as it is.
- I see.

741
00:55:40,124 --> 00:55:43,752
Perhaps I could write to the State
Senate and request funds from them.

742
00:55:43,953 --> 00:55:45,835
As far as they're concerned,
there's only three ways to spend...

743
00:55:45,836 --> 00:55:48,014
...tax paying hard than money
when it comes to prisons.

744
00:55:48,415 --> 00:55:50,483
more walls, more bars and more guards.

745
00:55:50,484 --> 00:55:55,188
Still, I'd like to try, with your permission. A
letter a week. They can't ignore me forever.

746
00:55:55,189 --> 00:55:56,014
Sure can.

747
00:55:56,715 --> 00:55:58,976
But you write your letters,
if it makes you happy.

748
00:55:59,477 --> 00:56:02,150
I'll even mail them for you. How's that?

749
00:56:03,889 --> 00:56:08,582
<i>So, Andy started writing
a letter a week,... just like he said.</i>

750
00:56:12,949 --> 00:56:17,457
<i>And, just like Norton said,
Andy got no answers.</i>

751
00:56:25,119 --> 00:56:30,007
<i>The following April, Andy did tax returns
for half the guards at Shawshank.</i>

752
00:56:31,508 --> 00:56:33,677
<i>The year after that, he did them all...</i>

753
00:56:33,678 --> 00:56:35,642
<i>including the Warden's.</i>

754
00:56:37,839 --> 00:56:40,976
<i>The year after that, they rescheduled
the start of the intramural season</i>

755
00:56:40,977 --> 00:56:43,441
<i>to coincide with tax season.</i>

756
00:56:45,356 --> 00:56:49,651
<i>The guards on the opposing teams
all remembered to bring their W-2s.</i>

757
00:56:49,652 --> 00:56:53,963
So, Moresby Prison issued you
your gun, but you had to pay for it?

758
00:56:53,964 --> 00:56:55,699
Damn right. The holster, too.

759
00:56:55,700 --> 00:56:58,284
That's tax-deductible. You can write that off.

760
00:56:58,285 --> 00:57:01,705
<i>Yes, sir. Andy was a
regular cottage industry.</i>

761
00:57:02,206 --> 00:57:04,833
<i>In fact, it got so busy at tax time...</i>

762
00:57:04,834 --> 00:57:06,760
<i>he was allowed a staff.</i>

763
00:57:07,161 --> 00:57:09,504
Hey, Red, can you
hand me a stack of 1040s?

764
00:57:09,705 --> 00:57:12,257
<i>It got me out of the wood shop
a month out of the year,</i>

765
00:57:12,258 --> 00:57:14,410
<i>and that was fine by me.</i>

766
00:57:15,811 --> 00:57:18,768
<i>And still... he kept
sending those letters.</i>

767
00:57:23,686 --> 00:57:25,603
Red... Andy.

768
00:57:25,604 --> 00:57:26,896
It's Brooks.

769
00:57:26,897 --> 00:57:28,941
Watch the door.

770
00:57:29,442 --> 00:57:32,509
- Please, Brooks.
- Just calm the fuck down.

771
00:57:32,510 --> 00:57:33,194
Stay back!

772
00:57:33,595 --> 00:57:35,421
- Stay back!
- What the hell's going on?

773
00:57:35,422 --> 00:57:38,491
You tell me. One second he's fine.
Then out comes the knife.

774
00:57:38,792 --> 00:57:41,036
Brooks, we can talk about this. Right?

775
00:57:41,037 --> 00:57:43,246
Nothing to talk about, goddamn it!

776
00:57:43,247 --> 00:57:45,040
I'm gonna cut his fucking throat.

777
00:57:45,041 --> 00:57:47,000
Heywood? Wait, what's he done to you?

778
00:57:47,001 --> 00:57:48,610
It's what they done!

779
00:57:49,511 --> 00:57:50,912
I... I got no choice...

780
00:57:50,913 --> 00:57:53,865
You're not gonna hurt Heywood.
we all know even Heywood knows that.

781
00:57:53,866 --> 00:57:56,076
- Right, Heywood?
- I... I know that, sure.

782
00:57:56,077 --> 00:57:59,779
You won't hurt him, because he's a friend of
yours and Brooks has been a reasonable man.

783
00:57:59,780 --> 00:58:01,056
That's right. That's right, guys?

784
00:58:01,057 --> 00:58:04,717
- Yes.
- So, put the knife down. Brooks, look at me.

785
00:58:04,718 --> 00:58:06,432
Put the knife down.

786
00:58:07,438 --> 00:58:08,388
Brooks...

787
00:58:08,889 --> 00:58:10,624
Look at his neck, for God's sake.

788
00:58:11,925 --> 00:58:13,443
Brooks, look at his neck. It's bleeding.

789
00:58:14,695 --> 00:58:15,862
It's the only...

790
00:58:16,763 --> 00:58:18,740
It's the only way they'd let me stay.

791
00:58:18,741 --> 00:58:21,326
Come on. This is crazy.
You don't want to do this, come on.

792
00:58:21,727 --> 00:58:23,291
Put it down.

793
00:58:30,995 --> 00:58:35,590
Come on. Take it easy.
You're going to be all right.

794
00:58:36,091 --> 00:58:36,850
Him?

795
00:58:37,151 --> 00:58:41,204
Hell, what about me?
Crazy old fool damn near cut my throat.

796
00:58:41,205 --> 00:58:43,515
Shit, Heywood,
you've had worse from shaving.

797
00:58:43,816 --> 00:58:45,450
What the hell did you
do to set him off, anyway?

798
00:58:45,451 --> 00:58:48,269
I do nothing. I come in
here to say fare-thee-well.

799
00:58:48,870 --> 00:58:51,277
Ain't you heard? His parole's come through.

800
00:58:53,842 --> 00:58:56,553
I just don't understand what
happened in there. That's all.

801
00:58:56,554 --> 00:58:59,522
The old man's as crazy
as a rat in a tin shithouse.

802
00:58:59,523 --> 00:59:01,616
Oh, Heywood, that's enough out of you.

803
00:59:02,017 --> 00:59:04,802
- I heard he had you shitting in your pants.
- Fuck you!

804
00:59:04,803 --> 00:59:06,162
Would you knock it off?

805
00:59:07,063 --> 00:59:08,581
Brooks ain't no bug.

806
00:59:09,082 --> 00:59:10,038
He's just...

807
00:59:12,336 --> 00:59:14,550
He's just institutionalized.

808
00:59:15,506 --> 00:59:17,757
Institutionalized, my ass.

809
00:59:17,758 --> 00:59:21,636
The man's been in here
50 years, Heywood. 50 years.

810
00:59:21,637 --> 00:59:23,129
This is all he knows.

811
00:59:23,830 --> 00:59:25,932
In here, he's an important man.

812
00:59:26,273 --> 00:59:27,475
He's an educated man.

813
00:59:28,276 --> 00:59:29,941
Outside, he's nothing.

814
00:59:30,930 --> 00:59:33,940
Just a used-up con with
arthritis in both hands.

815
00:59:34,641 --> 00:59:37,235
Probably couldn't get
a library card if he tried.

816
00:59:37,836 --> 00:59:39,404
You know what I'm trying to say?

817
00:59:40,105 --> 00:59:42,837
Red, I do believe you're
talking out of your ass.

818
00:59:44,309 --> 00:59:46,328
You believe whatever you want, Floyd.

819
00:59:47,029 --> 00:59:49,252
But I'm telling you, these walls are funny.

820
00:59:50,991 --> 00:59:52,556
First you hate 'em...

821
00:59:54,720 --> 00:59:56,384
...then you get used to 'em.

822
00:59:58,332 --> 01:00:00,342
Enough time passes...

823
01:00:01,043 --> 01:00:03,187
you get so you depend on 'em.

824
01:00:03,988 --> 01:00:06,106
That's institutionalized.

825
01:00:06,607 --> 01:00:07,682
Shit.

826
01:00:07,683 --> 01:00:09,392
You can never get like that.

827
01:00:09,393 --> 01:00:10,894
Oh, yeah?

828
01:00:11,595 --> 01:00:14,063
Say that when you've been
here as long as Brooks has.

829
01:00:14,364 --> 01:00:15,820
Goddamn right.

830
01:00:18,277 --> 01:00:20,204
They send you here for life.

831
01:00:21,255 --> 01:00:23,369
That's exactly what they take.

832
01:00:25,109 --> 01:00:26,873
The part that counts, anyway.

833
01:00:34,501 --> 01:00:37,249
I can't take care of you no more, Jake.

834
01:00:38,789 --> 01:00:40,303
You go on, now.

835
01:00:41,708 --> 01:00:43,059
You're free.

836
01:00:44,608 --> 01:00:45,559
You're free.

837
01:01:02,471 --> 01:01:03,827
Bye.

838
01:01:05,032 --> 01:01:06,830
Good luck, Brooks.

839
01:01:44,929 --> 01:01:46,322
<i>Dear fellas...</i>

840
01:01:46,823 --> 01:01:50,818
<i>I can't believe how fast
things move on the outside.</i>

841
01:01:52,354 --> 01:01:54,681
<i>Watch it, old-timer! Are
you trying to get killed?</i>

842
01:01:55,982 --> 01:01:59,501
<i>I saw an automobile once,
when I was a kid, but...</i>

843
01:02:00,102 --> 01:02:02,301
<i>now... they're everywhere.</i>

844
01:02:06,034 --> 01:02:09,900
<i>The world went and got
itself in a big damn hurry.</i>

845
01:02:26,571 --> 01:02:32,351
<i>The parole board got me into
this halfway house called The Brewer,</i>

846
01:02:32,352 --> 01:02:36,327
<i>and a job, bagging groceries at the Foodway.</i>

847
01:02:37,991 --> 01:02:43,412
<i>It's hard work, and I try to keep up,
but my hands hurt most of the time.</i>

848
01:02:43,413 --> 01:02:45,398
Make sure your man double-bags.

849
01:02:45,399 --> 01:02:48,433
Last time, he didn't double-bags.
The bottom near came out.

850
01:02:48,434 --> 01:02:51,512
Make sure you double-bag,
like the lady says. Understand?

851
01:02:51,513 --> 01:02:52,855
Yes, sir. I surely will.

852
01:02:52,856 --> 01:02:56,434
<i>I don't think the store
manager likes me very much.</i>

853
01:02:59,713 --> 01:03:04,192
<i>Sometimes, after work,
I go to the park and feed the birds.</i>

854
01:03:04,493 --> 01:03:09,614
<i>I keep thinking... Jake might
just show up and say hello.</i>

855
01:03:09,915 --> 01:03:11,787
<i>But he never does.</i>

856
01:03:13,193 --> 01:03:18,252
<i>I hope, wherever he is,
he's doing OK and making new friends.</i>

857
01:03:21,677 --> 01:03:24,379
<i>I have trouble sleeping at night.</i>

858
01:03:24,780 --> 01:03:27,553
<i>I have bad dreams, like I'm falling.</i>

859
01:03:28,558 --> 01:03:30,559
<i>I wake up, scared.</i>

860
01:03:30,760 --> 01:03:34,743
<i>Sometimes it takes me a while
to remember where I am.</i>

861
01:03:36,391 --> 01:03:41,836
<i>Maybe I should get me a gun and rob
the Foodway, so they'd send me home.</i>

862
01:03:41,897 --> 01:03:44,115
<i>I could shoot the
manager, while I was at it.</i>

863
01:03:44,316 --> 01:03:46,155
<i>Sort of like a bonus.</i>

864
01:03:47,677 --> 01:03:51,614
<i>I guess I'm too old for that
sort of nonsense any more.</i>

865
01:03:52,115 --> 01:03:53,741
<i>I don't like it here.</i>

866
01:03:53,742 --> 01:03:56,494
<i>I'm tired of being afraid all the time.</i>

867
01:03:56,895 --> 01:03:57,962
<i>I've decided...</i>

868
01:03:58,563 --> 01:03:59,919
<i>not to stay.</i>

869
01:04:11,084 --> 01:04:17,036
<i>I doubt they'll kick up any fuss.
Not for an old crook like me.</i>

870
01:05:20,178 --> 01:05:24,203
"I doubt they'll kick up any fuss.
Not for an old crook like me.

871
01:05:25,091 --> 01:05:29,136
PS. Tell Heywood I'm sorry
I put a knife to his throat.

872
01:05:29,137 --> 01:05:31,002
No hard feelings. Brooks."

873
01:05:41,942 --> 01:05:43,606
He should have died in here.

874
01:05:49,249 --> 01:05:53,191
What the fuck have you done?
It's a goddamn mess. I'll tell you that.

875
01:05:59,225 --> 01:06:00,125
What's all this?

876
01:06:00,126 --> 01:06:02,688
You tell me, fuck-stick.
They're all addressed to you.

877
01:06:04,369 --> 01:06:05,561
Take it.

878
01:06:14,049 --> 01:06:15,813
"Dear Mr. Dufresne...

879
01:06:16,718 --> 01:06:19,103
In response to your repeated inquiries,

880
01:06:19,104 --> 01:06:23,099
the State has allocated the enclosed
funds for your library project."

881
01:06:24,400 --> 01:06:25,356
This is 200 dollars.

882
01:06:26,119 --> 01:06:29,722
"In addition, the Library District
has generously responded

883
01:06:29,723 --> 01:06:32,817
with a charitable donation
of used books and sundries.

884
01:06:33,118 --> 01:06:34,986
We trust this will fill your needs.

885
01:06:35,387 --> 01:06:39,398
We now consider the matter closed.
Please stop sending us letters."

886
01:06:39,599 --> 01:06:42,318
I want all this cleared out
before the Warden gets back.

887
01:06:42,319 --> 01:06:43,166
Yes, sir.

888
01:06:47,941 --> 01:06:49,296
Good for you, Andy.

889
01:06:51,945 --> 01:06:52,884
Wow!

890
01:06:54,289 --> 01:06:56,053
It only took six years.

891
01:06:57,867 --> 01:07:00,578
From now on, I'll write two
letters a week, instead of one.

892
01:07:00,579 --> 01:07:04,156
Oh, I believe you're crazy enough.
You'd better get all this stuff out here,

893
01:07:04,157 --> 01:07:05,208
like the Captain said.

894
01:07:05,609 --> 01:07:10,366
Now, I'm gonna go pinch a loaf.
When I come back, this is all gone, right?

895
01:07:15,660 --> 01:07:16,741
Wow.

896
01:07:51,605 --> 01:07:54,570
<i>♪ Sull'aria... ♪</i>

897
01:07:58,719 --> 01:08:00,121
Andy, do you hear that?

898
01:08:00,322 --> 01:08:04,413
<i>♪ ...zeffiretto ♪</i>

899
01:08:16,254 --> 01:08:24,475
<i>♪ Questa sera spirera ♪</i>

900
01:08:54,701 --> 01:08:58,879
<i>♪ Sotto i pini ♪</i>

901
01:08:58,880 --> 01:09:04,473
<i>♪ Del boschetto ♪</i>

902
01:09:05,795 --> 01:09:08,055
<i>♪ Sotto i pini... ♪</i>

903
01:09:08,056 --> 01:09:10,516
<i>Dufresne?</i>

904
01:09:11,317 --> 01:09:12,085
<i>Dufresne?</i>

905
01:09:12,986 --> 01:09:14,450
<i>Andy, let me out.</i>

906
01:09:17,582 --> 01:09:18,710
<i>Andy?</i>

907
01:09:21,311 --> 01:09:26,065
<i>I have no idea to this day what
those two Italian ladies were singing about.</i>

908
01:09:26,766 --> 01:09:29,068
<i>The truth is, I don't want to know.</i>

909
01:09:29,369 --> 01:09:31,533
<i>Some things are best left unsaid.</i>

910
01:09:35,200 --> 01:09:37,901
<i>I like to think they were singing
about something so beautiful,...</i>

911
01:09:37,902 --> 01:09:43,086
<i>...it can't be expressed in words,... and
makes your heart ache because of it.</i>

912
01:09:44,918 --> 01:09:47,611
<i>I tell you, those voices soared...</i>

913
01:09:47,612 --> 01:09:51,941
<i>higher and farther than anybody
in a gray place dares to dream.</i>

914
01:09:52,342 --> 01:09:55,783
<i>It was like some beautiful bird
flapped into our drab little cage</i>

915
01:09:55,784 --> 01:09:58,314
<i>and made those walls dissolve away.</i>

916
01:09:59,015 --> 01:10:00,733
<i>And for the briefest of moments...</i>

917
01:10:01,334 --> 01:10:04,500
<i>every last man at Shawshank felt free.</i>

918
01:10:07,223 --> 01:10:09,705
<i>It pissed the Warden off something awful.</i>

919
01:10:11,144 --> 01:10:12,449
Open the door.

920
01:10:14,723 --> 01:10:16,420
Open it up!

921
01:10:18,151 --> 01:10:20,411
Dufresne, open this door!

922
01:10:21,955 --> 01:10:23,372
Turn that off!

923
01:10:30,288 --> 01:10:33,420
I am warning you,
Dufresne. Turn that off!

924
01:10:46,688 --> 01:10:48,044
Dufresne...

925
01:10:50,491 --> 01:10:51,955
<i>You're mine now.</i>

926
01:10:59,425 --> 01:11:02,461
<i>Andy got two weeks in
the hole for that little stunt.</i>

927
01:11:02,462 --> 01:11:04,260
On your feet!

928
01:11:05,890 --> 01:11:07,855
- Hey, look who's here.
- Maestro!

929
01:11:09,477 --> 01:11:13,605
Y-Y-You couldn't play something good, huh?
Hank Williams or something?

930
01:11:13,606 --> 01:11:16,358
They broke the door down
before I could take requests.

931
01:11:16,359 --> 01:11:18,235
Was it worth it, two weeks in the hole?

932
01:11:18,236 --> 01:11:19,570
Easiest time I ever did.

933
01:11:19,571 --> 01:11:22,614
Bullshit! There's no such
thing as easy time in the hole.

934
01:11:22,615 --> 01:11:24,825
A week in the hole is like a year.

935
01:11:25,326 --> 01:11:27,620
I had Mr. Mozart to keep me company.

936
01:11:28,121 --> 01:11:30,536
So, they let you tote that
record player down there, huh?

937
01:11:33,585 --> 01:11:34,794
It was in here.

938
01:11:35,295 --> 01:11:36,842
And in here.

939
01:11:38,173 --> 01:11:42,306
That's the beauty of music.
They can't get that from you.

940
01:11:46,347 --> 01:11:48,229
Haven't you ever felt that way about music?

941
01:11:50,518 --> 01:11:53,288
Well, I played a mean harmonica,
as a younger man.

942
01:11:54,689 --> 01:11:56,065
Lost interest in it, though.

943
01:11:56,566 --> 01:11:57,983
Didn't make much sense in here.

944
01:11:58,484 --> 01:12:00,128
Here's where it makes the most sense.

945
01:12:01,029 --> 01:12:02,997
You need it, so you don't forget.

946
01:12:03,698 --> 01:12:04,615
Forget?

947
01:12:05,116 --> 01:12:06,659
Forget that...

948
01:12:07,160 --> 01:12:09,124
there are places...

949
01:12:10,580 --> 01:12:14,434
...in the world that aren't made
out of stone... that there's a...

950
01:12:15,335 --> 01:12:16,752
there's something...

951
01:12:17,153 --> 01:12:20,430
inside that,... they can't get to... that...

952
01:12:20,771 --> 01:12:22,107
they can't touch.

953
01:12:22,908 --> 01:12:24,264
It's yours.

954
01:12:25,703 --> 01:12:26,892
What are you talking about?

955
01:12:28,580 --> 01:12:29,765
Hope.

956
01:12:30,566 --> 01:12:31,622
Hope?

957
01:12:33,978 --> 01:12:35,530
Let me tell you something, my friend.

958
01:12:36,581 --> 01:12:38,570
Hope is a dangerous thing.

959
01:12:40,076 --> 01:12:42,199
Hope can drive a man insane.

960
01:12:43,363 --> 01:12:44,864
It's got no use on the inside.

961
01:12:45,465 --> 01:12:47,513
You'd better get used to that idea.

962
01:12:50,253 --> 01:12:51,959
Like Brooks did?

963
01:13:17,313 --> 01:13:18,235
Sit down.

964
01:13:23,569 --> 01:13:26,614
It says here that you've served
30 years of a life sentence.

965
01:13:28,015 --> 01:13:29,825
You feel you've been rehabilitated?

966
01:13:30,326 --> 01:13:31,410
Oh, yes, sir.

967
01:13:32,811 --> 01:13:33,876
Without a doubt.

968
01:13:35,139 --> 01:13:37,254
And I can honestly say I'm a changed man.

969
01:13:39,761 --> 01:13:41,587
No danger to society here.

970
01:13:42,188 --> 01:13:43,652
God's honest truth.

971
01:13:46,409 --> 01:13:48,173
Absolutely rehabilitated.

972
01:13:58,321 --> 01:13:59,585
30 years.

973
01:14:01,691 --> 01:14:03,317
Jesus, when they say it like that...

974
01:14:04,518 --> 01:14:05,782
You wonder where it went.

975
01:14:08,665 --> 01:14:10,329
I wonder where ten years went.

976
01:14:15,797 --> 01:14:16,872
Here.

977
01:14:17,373 --> 01:14:19,421
Little parole rejection present.

978
01:14:21,377 --> 01:14:22,603
Go ahead and open it.

979
01:14:24,404 --> 01:14:27,382
I had to go through one of your
competitors. I hope you don't mind.

980
01:14:27,383 --> 01:14:28,848
I wanted it to be a surprise.

981
01:14:39,604 --> 01:14:40,968
It's very pretty, Andy.

982
01:14:42,774 --> 01:14:43,938
Thank you.

983
01:14:46,411 --> 01:14:47,775
Are you going to play it?

984
01:14:52,625 --> 01:14:53,690
No.

985
01:14:57,105 --> 01:14:58,669
Not right now.

986
01:15:06,547 --> 01:15:08,512
<i>Tier 3 South. Clear.</i>

987
01:15:09,675 --> 01:15:11,302
<i>Tier 4 North. Clear.</i>

988
01:15:11,803 --> 01:15:13,767
<i>Tier 1 South. Clear.</i>

989
01:15:16,724 --> 01:15:17,589
<i>Fall in!</i>

990
01:15:53,686 --> 01:15:54,553
<i>Lights out!</i>

991
01:16:29,881 --> 01:16:31,507
<i>Andy was as good as his word.</i>

992
01:16:32,108 --> 01:16:34,489
<i>He wrote two letters
a week instead of one.</i>

993
01:16:37,138 --> 01:16:40,949
<i>In 1959, the State Senate
finally clued into the fact</i>

994
01:16:40,950 --> 01:16:44,111
<i>they couldn't buy him off
with just a $200 check.</i>

995
01:16:44,512 --> 01:16:50,984
<i>Appropriations Committee voted an
annual payment of $500 just to shut him up.</i>

996
01:16:51,185 --> 01:16:54,029
<i>And you'd be amazed how
far Andy could stretch it.</i>

997
01:16:54,530 --> 01:16:57,491
<i>He made deals with book
clubs, charity groups.</i>

998
01:16:57,492 --> 01:16:59,951
<i>He bought remaindered
books by the pound.</i>

999
01:17:00,952 --> 01:17:02,245
Treasure Island.

1000
01:17:02,646 --> 01:17:04,398
Robert Louis...

1001
01:17:04,399 --> 01:17:05,290
...Stevenson.

1002
01:17:05,791 --> 01:17:07,430
Fiction, adventure.

1003
01:17:09,453 --> 01:17:10,579
What's next?

1004
01:17:10,880 --> 01:17:13,770
I got here Auto Repair and...

1005
01:17:14,634 --> 01:17:15,851
...Soap Carving.

1006
01:17:16,052 --> 01:17:19,513
Trade skills and hobbies. Goes under
Educational. The stack behind you.

1007
01:17:19,514 --> 01:17:21,540
The Count Of Monte Crisco.

1008
01:17:21,641 --> 01:17:23,859
That's Cristo, you dumb shit.

1009
01:17:24,160 --> 01:17:27,738
By Alexandree... Dumass.

1010
01:17:28,339 --> 01:17:29,739
Dumb-ass?

1011
01:17:31,639 --> 01:17:32,739
Dumb-ass?

1012
01:17:35,363 --> 01:17:37,681
Dumas. You know what that's about?

1013
01:17:38,082 --> 01:17:38,741
Uh-uh.

1014
01:17:39,642 --> 01:17:41,835
You'll like it. It's about a prison break.

1015
01:17:42,036 --> 01:17:45,422
We ought to file that under
Educational, too, oughtn't we?

1016
01:17:46,823 --> 01:17:50,473
<i>The rest of us did our best to
pitch in when and where we could.</i>

1017
01:17:51,546 --> 01:17:53,263
<i>By the year Kennedy was shot,</i>

1018
01:17:53,464 --> 01:17:58,101
<i>Andy had transformed a storage room
smelling of rat turds and turpentine</i>

1019
01:17:58,102 --> 01:18:01,221
<i>into the best prison
library in New England,</i>

1020
01:18:01,822 --> 01:18:05,083
<i>complete with a fine
selection of Hank Williams.</i>

1021
01:18:05,484 --> 01:18:08,937
<i>♪ Lawd I don't know what I'll do-ooo ♪</i>

1022
01:18:09,238 --> 01:18:12,074
<i>♪ All I do is sit and sigh... ♪</i>

1023
01:18:12,475 --> 01:18:17,312
<i>That was also the year Warden Norton
instituted his famous Inside Out program.</i>

1024
01:18:17,813 --> 01:18:19,906
<i>You may remember reading about it.</i>

1025
01:18:20,307 --> 01:18:23,210
<i>It made all the papers and got
his picture in Look Magazine.</i>

1026
01:18:23,211 --> 01:18:24,661
No free ride.

1027
01:18:25,162 --> 01:18:30,555
But rather a genuine, progressive advance,
in corrections and rehabilitation.

1028
01:18:31,319 --> 01:18:33,737
Our inmates, properly supervised,

1029
01:18:34,138 --> 01:18:36,573
will be put to work outside these walls,

1030
01:18:36,974 --> 01:18:39,142
performing all manner of public service.

1031
01:18:39,743 --> 01:18:42,846
These men can learn the
value of an honest day's labor,

1032
01:18:43,047 --> 01:18:46,600
while providing a valuable
service to the community and...

1033
01:18:47,101 --> 01:18:51,896
at a bare minimum of expense
to Mr. and Mrs. John Q Taxpayer.

1034
01:18:51,897 --> 01:18:54,649
<i>Of course, Norton failed
to mention to the press</i>

1035
01:18:54,650 --> 01:18:58,028
<i>that "bare minimum of expense"
is a fairly loose term.</i>

1036
01:18:58,729 --> 01:19:01,281
<i>There are a hundred different
ways to skim off the top.</i>

1037
01:19:01,282 --> 01:19:03,788
<i>Men, materials, you name it.</i>

1038
01:19:04,952 --> 01:19:07,787
<i>And, oh, my Lord,
how the money rolled in.</i>

1039
01:19:07,788 --> 01:19:09,998
If this keeps up, you'll
put me out of business.

1040
01:19:09,999 --> 01:19:12,250
- Ned!
- This pool of slave labor you've got,

1041
01:19:12,251 --> 01:19:14,377
you can underbid any contractor in town.

1042
01:19:14,378 --> 01:19:18,423
Ned,... we're providing
a valuable community service here.

1043
01:19:18,424 --> 01:19:21,844
Well, that's fine for the papers
but I've got a family to feed.

1044
01:19:22,345 --> 01:19:22,937
Sam...

1045
01:19:24,938 --> 01:19:26,681
Sam, we go back a long way.

1046
01:19:27,782 --> 01:19:32,121
I need this new highway contract.
I don't get it, and I go under. That's a fact.

1047
01:19:33,522 --> 01:19:37,217
You just have some of this fine pie
my missus made especially for you,

1048
01:19:37,818 --> 01:19:39,332
and you think about that.

1049
01:19:47,203 --> 01:19:49,705
Ned, I wouldn't worry too
much about this contract.

1050
01:19:50,206 --> 01:19:53,296
It seems to me I already got
my boys committed elsewhere.

1051
01:19:55,294 --> 01:19:57,959
You be sure and thank
Maisie for this fine pie.

1052
01:19:59,507 --> 01:20:01,558
<i>And behind every shady deal,</i>

1053
01:20:01,859 --> 01:20:04,052
<i>behind every dollar earned,</i>

1054
01:20:04,853 --> 01:20:07,402
<i>there was Andy,
keeping the books.</i>

1055
01:20:08,265 --> 01:20:11,768
Two deposits. Maine National
and New England First.

1056
01:20:11,769 --> 01:20:13,433
Night drops as always, sir.

1057
01:20:44,260 --> 01:20:45,594
Get my stuff down to the laundry.

1058
01:20:46,095 --> 01:20:48,072
Two suits for dry-clean and a bag of whatnot.

1059
01:20:48,073 --> 01:20:48,872
Yes, sir.

1060
01:20:48,973 --> 01:20:51,909
Tell them if they over-starch my shirts
again, they'll hear about it from me.

1061
01:20:51,910 --> 01:20:52,809
Yes, sir.

1062
01:20:52,810 --> 01:20:53,994
How do I look?

1063
01:20:54,895 --> 01:20:57,689
- Very nice, sir.
- Big charity to-do up Portland way.

1064
01:20:57,690 --> 01:20:59,079
The Governor's going to be there.

1065
01:21:00,618 --> 01:21:01,944
Want the rest of this?

1066
01:21:03,245 --> 01:21:05,109
The woman can't bake worth shit.

1067
01:21:06,407 --> 01:21:07,779
Thank you, sir.

1068
01:21:10,569 --> 01:21:14,305
- He's got his fingers in a lot of pies, I hear.
- What you hear isn't half of it.

1069
01:21:14,306 --> 01:21:16,650
He's got scams you
haven't even dreamed of.

1070
01:21:16,751 --> 01:21:18,777
Kickbacks on his kickbacks.

1071
01:21:18,878 --> 01:21:21,838
There's a river of dirty money
running through this place.

1072
01:21:21,839 --> 01:21:24,875
But the problem with having all that
money is you'll have to explain...

1073
01:21:24,876 --> 01:21:27,344
- where it came from.
- That's where I come in.

1074
01:21:28,045 --> 01:21:30,430
I channel it, filter it, funnel it.

1075
01:21:30,431 --> 01:21:33,157
Stocks, securities, tax-free municipals.

1076
01:21:33,858 --> 01:21:35,910
I send that money out into the real world.

1077
01:21:36,011 --> 01:21:39,522
- And when it comes back...
- Clean as a virgin's honey pot, huh?

1078
01:21:39,523 --> 01:21:40,315
Cleaner.

1079
01:21:40,816 --> 01:21:44,324
By the time Norton retires,
I'll have made him a millionaire.

1080
01:21:47,198 --> 01:21:51,201
If they ever catch on, though, he's gonna
wind up in here wearing a number himself.

1081
01:21:51,702 --> 01:21:54,738
Now, Red, I thought you had
a little more faith in me than that.

1082
01:21:54,739 --> 01:21:57,916
I know you're good, Andy,
but all that paper leaves a trail.

1083
01:21:58,317 --> 01:22:02,503
Now, anybody gets curious,
the FBI, the IRS, whatever,

1084
01:22:03,004 --> 01:22:06,166
- it's gonna lead to somebody.
- Sure it is. But not to me.

1085
01:22:06,167 --> 01:22:07,948
And certainly not to the Warden.

1086
01:22:12,515 --> 01:22:13,730
All right. Who?

1087
01:22:13,791 --> 01:22:15,183
Randall Stevens.

1088
01:22:15,884 --> 01:22:16,731
Who?

1089
01:22:17,137 --> 01:22:22,232
The silent silent partner. He's the guilty one,
Your Honor. The man with the bank accounts.

1090
01:22:22,733 --> 01:22:24,684
That's where the filtering process starts.

1091
01:22:24,785 --> 01:22:27,438
If they trace anything,
it's just going to lead to him.

1092
01:22:28,239 --> 01:22:29,406
But who is he?

1093
01:22:29,707 --> 01:22:31,833
He's a phantom, an apparition.

1094
01:22:32,034 --> 01:22:34,077
Second cousin to Harvey the Rabbit.

1095
01:22:34,978 --> 01:22:37,656
I conjured him... out of thin air.

1096
01:22:38,457 --> 01:22:41,472
He doesn't exist, except on paper.

1097
01:22:44,221 --> 01:22:46,881
Andy, you can't just make a person up.

1098
01:22:46,882 --> 01:22:50,093
Sure you can, if you know how the
system works, where the cracks are.

1099
01:22:50,494 --> 01:22:53,180
It's amazing what you
can accomplish by mail.

1100
01:22:53,481 --> 01:22:58,810
Mr. Stevens has a birth certificate,
a driver's license, social security number.

1101
01:22:59,111 --> 01:23:00,003
You're shitting me?

1102
01:23:00,004 --> 01:23:01,946
If they ever trace any of those accounts,

1103
01:23:01,947 --> 01:23:04,608
they're going to wind up chasing
a figment of my imagination.

1104
01:23:05,109 --> 01:23:07,073
Well, I'll be damned.

1105
01:23:08,787 --> 01:23:10,313
Did I say you were good?

1106
01:23:10,914 --> 01:23:12,566
Shit, you're a Rembrandt!

1107
01:23:13,267 --> 01:23:14,793
You know, the funny thing is,

1108
01:23:14,994 --> 01:23:18,835
on the outside, I was an honest
man, straight as an arrow.

1109
01:23:19,799 --> 01:23:22,255
I had to come to prison to be a crook.

1110
01:23:31,135 --> 01:23:32,570
Ever bother you?

1111
01:23:33,554 --> 01:23:36,956
I don't run the scams, Red,
I just process the profits.

1112
01:23:37,057 --> 01:23:38,683
Fine line maybe but...

1113
01:23:39,534 --> 01:23:41,878
I also built that library

1114
01:23:41,979 --> 01:23:44,889
and used it to help a dozen guys
get a high school diploma.

1115
01:23:44,990 --> 01:23:47,049
Why do you think the Warden lets me do it?

1116
01:23:47,550 --> 01:23:49,485
To keep you happy and doing the laundry.

1117
01:23:50,086 --> 01:23:51,496
Money instead of sheets.

1118
01:23:51,697 --> 01:23:54,290
Well, I work cheap. That's the trade-off.

1119
01:24:10,007 --> 01:24:11,883
<i>♪ I know a cat named... ♪</i>

1120
01:24:11,884 --> 01:24:14,436
<i>Tommy Williams
came to Shawshank in 1965</i>

1121
01:24:14,437 --> 01:24:16,263
<i>on a two-year stretch for B&E.</i>

1122
01:24:16,964 --> 01:24:18,873
<i>That's "breaking and entering" to you.</i>

1123
01:24:19,674 --> 01:24:23,386
<i>The cops caught him sneaking TV sets
out the back door of a JC Penney.</i>

1124
01:24:24,087 --> 01:24:25,521
<i>Young punk.</i>

1125
01:24:25,822 --> 01:24:27,149
<i>Mr. Rock'n'roll.</i>

1126
01:24:27,650 --> 01:24:28,900
<i>Cocky as hell.</i>

1127
01:24:29,401 --> 01:24:33,930
Hey, come on, old boys! Moving like
molasses! Making me look bad.

1128
01:24:34,031 --> 01:24:35,574
<i>We liked him immediately.</i>

1129
01:24:36,075 --> 01:24:37,701
So I'm backing out the door, right?

1130
01:24:38,202 --> 01:24:39,994
And I got the TV like this.

1131
01:24:40,295 --> 01:24:43,915
It was a big old thing. I couldn't see shit.
Suddenly, I hears this voice.

1132
01:24:43,916 --> 01:24:46,042
"Freeze, kid! Hands in the air."

1133
01:24:46,043 --> 01:24:47,794
Well, I just stand there,

1134
01:24:47,795 --> 01:24:50,672
holding onto that TV. So,
finally, the voice says,

1135
01:24:50,673 --> 01:24:52,715
"Do you hear what I said, boy?"

1136
01:24:52,716 --> 01:24:55,176
I say, "Yes, sir, I sure did.

1137
01:24:55,177 --> 01:24:58,988
But if I drop this fucking thing,
you got me on destruction of property, too."

1138
01:25:02,893 --> 01:25:05,987
Hey, you've done a
stretch in Cashman, right?

1139
01:25:05,988 --> 01:25:09,607
Yeah. Yeah, that was an easy
piece of time, let me tell you.

1140
01:25:09,908 --> 01:25:12,318
Weekend furloughs, work programs.

1141
01:25:12,519 --> 01:25:13,820
Not like here.

1142
01:25:14,121 --> 01:25:16,239
Sounds like you done time
all over New England.

1143
01:25:16,240 --> 01:25:18,992
Yeah, I've been in and out since I was 13.

1144
01:25:18,993 --> 01:25:21,211
You name the place,
chances are I've been there.

1145
01:25:21,412 --> 01:25:23,698
Perhaps it's time you tried a new profession?

1146
01:25:25,499 --> 01:25:30,970
What I mean is, you don't seem to be a good
thief. Maybe you should try something else.

1147
01:25:31,071 --> 01:25:34,490
Yeah, well, what the hell
do you know about it, Capone?

1148
01:25:34,591 --> 01:25:36,026
What are you in for?

1149
01:25:36,627 --> 01:25:37,232
Me?

1150
01:25:39,855 --> 01:25:41,519
The lawyer fucked me.

1151
01:25:45,552 --> 01:25:49,051
Everybody's innocent in here.
Don't you know that?

1152
01:25:56,638 --> 01:26:00,688
<i>As it turned out, Tommy had himself
a young wife and a new baby girl.</i>

1153
01:26:01,452 --> 01:26:03,222
<i>Maybe it was the thought
of them on the streets...</i>

1154
01:26:03,223 --> 01:26:05,964
<i>or his child growing up
not knowing her daddy.</i>

1155
01:26:06,665 --> 01:26:10,681
<i>Whatever it was, something
lit a fire under that boy's ass.</i>

1156
01:26:14,465 --> 01:26:17,800
I was thinking of maybe trying
for my high school equivalency.

1157
01:26:17,801 --> 01:26:19,766
I hear you helped a couple of fellas with that.

1158
01:26:21,597 --> 01:26:23,686
I don't waste time on losers, Tommy.

1159
01:26:25,192 --> 01:26:27,357
I ain't no goddamn loser.

1160
01:26:29,113 --> 01:26:31,277
- You mean that?
- Yeah.

1161
01:26:32,667 --> 01:26:34,193
You really mean that?

1162
01:26:35,194 --> 01:26:36,944
Yes, sir, I do.

1163
01:26:36,945 --> 01:26:42,588
Good. Because if we do this, we do it
all the way, 100%, nothing half-assed.

1164
01:26:43,035 --> 01:26:44,999
The thing is, see...

1165
01:26:46,288 --> 01:26:48,002
...I don't read so good.

1166
01:26:48,949 --> 01:26:50,038
Well.

1167
01:26:52,211 --> 01:26:53,937
You don't read...

1168
01:26:54,138 --> 01:26:55,902
so well.

1169
01:26:57,883 --> 01:26:59,430
We'll get to that.

1170
01:27:00,786 --> 01:27:02,370
- R.
- R...

1171
01:27:02,471 --> 01:27:03,430
- S.
- S...

1172
01:27:03,631 --> 01:27:06,382
<i>- T...
- So Andy took Tommy under his wing.</i>

1173
01:27:06,383 --> 01:27:08,781
<i>He started walking
him through his ABCs.</i>

1174
01:27:11,070 --> 01:27:13,339
<i>Tommy took to it pretty well, too.</i>

1175
01:27:13,440 --> 01:27:16,180
<i>The boy found brains
he never knew he had.</i>

1176
01:27:18,637 --> 01:27:22,415
<i>Before long, Andy started him
on his course requirements.</i>

1177
01:27:22,416 --> 01:27:23,858
<i>He really liked the kid.</i>

1178
01:27:24,159 --> 01:27:27,208
<i>It gave him a thrill to help a youngster
crawl off the shit heap.</i>

1179
01:27:28,172 --> 01:27:30,498
<i>But that wasn't the only reason.</i>

1180
01:27:30,999 --> 01:27:32,839
<i>Prison time is slow time.</i>

