01:45:29,519 --> 01:45:31,345
These are just shitty pipe dreams.

1426
01:45:32,146 --> 01:45:34,689
I mean, Mexico is way the hell
down there and you're in here...

1427
01:45:34,690 --> 01:45:36,017
and that's the way it is.

1428
01:45:36,818 --> 01:45:39,424
Yeah, right. That's the way it is.

1429
01:45:40,997 --> 01:45:43,261
It's down there and I'm in here.

1430
01:45:45,893 --> 01:45:48,767
I guess it comes down
to a simple choice, really.

1431
01:45:51,524 --> 01:45:53,150
Get busy living

1432
01:45:54,251 --> 01:45:56,250
or get busy dying.

1433
01:46:00,366 --> 01:46:01,831
Andy.

1434
01:46:04,912 --> 01:46:06,077
Red.

1435
01:46:08,841 --> 01:46:11,142
If you ever get out of here, do me a favor.

1436
01:46:11,543 --> 01:46:12,561
Sure, Andy.

1437
01:46:13,362 --> 01:46:14,175
Anything.

1438
01:46:15,981 --> 01:46:18,921
There's a big hayfield up near Buxton.
You know where Buxton is?

1439
01:46:20,344 --> 01:46:23,222
Well, just... There's a lot
of hayfields up there.

1440
01:46:23,222 --> 01:46:28,451
One in particular. It's got a long rock wall,
with a big oak tree at the north end.

1441
01:46:28,452 --> 01:46:31,143
It's like something out
of a Robert Frost poem.

1442
01:46:32,540 --> 01:46:34,830
It's where I asked my wife to marry me.

1443
01:46:36,260 --> 01:46:40,635
We went there for a picnic
and made love under that oak.

1444
01:46:41,657 --> 01:46:43,622
I asked and she said yes.

1445
01:46:47,872 --> 01:46:49,498
Promise me, Red,

1446
01:46:50,299 --> 01:46:53,807
if you ever get out, find that spot.

1447
01:46:55,171 --> 01:47:00,017
At the base of that wall, you'll find a rock that
has no earthly business in a Maine hayfield.

1448
01:47:00,318 --> 01:47:03,800
A piece of black, volcanic glass.

1449
01:47:06,790 --> 01:47:09,767
There's something buried
under it, I want you to have.

1450
01:47:09,868 --> 01:47:11,353
What, Andy?

1451
01:47:11,854 --> 01:47:13,218
What's buried under there?

1452
01:47:15,233 --> 01:47:18,490
You'll have to pry it up... to see.

1453
01:47:24,250 --> 01:47:26,114
No, I'm telling you, the guy is...

1454
01:47:27,178 --> 01:47:28,645
He's talking funnier.

1455
01:47:29,747 --> 01:47:33,307
- I'm really worried about him.
- We ought to keep an eye on him.

1456
01:47:33,308 --> 01:47:36,833
That's fine during the day, but
at night he's got that cell all to himself.

1457
01:47:38,039 --> 01:47:39,581
Oh, Lord.

1458
01:47:40,582 --> 01:47:41,504
What?

1459
01:47:43,094 --> 01:47:45,512
Andy come down to the loading dock today.

1460
01:47:45,713 --> 01:47:49,199
- He asked me for a length of rope.
- Rope?

1461
01:47:49,200 --> 01:47:53,061
- Six feet long.
- And you gave it to him?

1462
01:47:53,462 --> 01:47:57,223
- Sure I did. Why wouldn't I?
- Jesus, Heywood.

1463
01:47:57,224 --> 01:47:59,559
Hey, how the hell was I supposed to know?

1464
01:47:59,860 --> 01:48:01,561
Remember Brooks Hatlen?

1465
01:48:01,562 --> 01:48:02,484
No.

1466
01:48:03,447 --> 01:48:05,157
Andy would never do that.

1467
01:48:05,858 --> 01:48:07,122
Never.

1468
01:48:08,986 --> 01:48:10,451
I don't know.

1469
01:48:12,915 --> 01:48:15,080
Every man has his breaking point.

1470
01:48:17,828 --> 01:48:19,862
Lickety-split. I want to get home.

1471
01:48:19,863 --> 01:48:21,920
Just about finished, sir.

1472
01:48:38,577 --> 01:48:40,505
Three deposits tonight.

1473
01:48:48,409 --> 01:48:50,293
Get my stuff down to the laundry.

1474
01:48:50,694 --> 01:48:54,239
And shine my shoes.
I want 'em looking like mirrors.

1475
01:48:54,640 --> 01:48:55,595
Yes, sir.

1476
01:49:00,913 --> 01:49:02,664
It's good having you back, Andy.

1477
01:49:03,165 --> 01:49:05,297
The place wasn't the same without you.

1478
01:49:52,065 --> 01:49:55,096
<i>Lights out!</i>

1479
01:50:25,956 --> 01:50:28,429
<u>I've had some long nights in stir.</u>

1480
01:50:29,193 --> 01:50:31,886
<i>Alone in the dark with
nothing but your thoughts,</i>

1481
01:50:31,987 --> 01:50:34,322
<i>time can draw out like a blade.</i>

1482
01:50:40,004 --> 01:50:42,919
<i>That was the longest night of my life.</i>

1483
01:50:58,781 --> 01:50:59,886
Give me a count.

1484
01:51:04,745 --> 01:51:06,871
Tier 3 South. Clear.

1485
01:51:06,872 --> 01:51:08,889
Tier 4 North. Clear.

1486
01:51:08,990 --> 01:51:13,360
- Tier 3 North. Clear.
- Man missing on Tier 2. Cell 245.

1487
01:51:13,561 --> 01:51:15,129
Dufresne.

1488
01:51:15,530 --> 01:51:17,929
Get your ass out here, boy.
You're holding up the show.

1489
01:51:20,753 --> 01:51:24,477
Don't make me come down there.
I'll thump your skull for you.

1490
01:51:31,989 --> 01:51:35,650
Damn it, Dufresne, you're putting me behind!
I got a schedule to keep.

1491
01:51:35,651 --> 01:51:38,820
You'd better be sick or dead in there,
I shit you not!

1492
01:51:39,321 --> 01:51:40,535
You hear me?

1493
01:51:47,162 --> 01:51:49,127
Oh, my holy God.

1494
01:52:06,098 --> 01:52:08,208
I want every man on
this cell block questioned.

1495
01:52:08,809 --> 01:52:11,102
- Start with that friend of his.
- Who?

1496
01:52:11,503 --> 01:52:12,592
Him!

1497
01:52:14,031 --> 01:52:15,696
Open 237.

1498
01:52:19,020 --> 01:52:21,529
What do you mean, he just wasn't here?

1499
01:52:21,830 --> 01:52:23,556
Don't say that to me, Haig.

1500
01:52:23,607 --> 01:52:25,291
Don't say that to me again.

1501
01:52:25,292 --> 01:52:28,011
- But, sir, he wasn't.
- I can see that, Haig!

1502
01:52:28,412 --> 01:52:29,605
You think I'm blind?

1503
01:52:30,706 --> 01:52:33,816
Is that what you're saying? Am I blind, Haig?

1504
01:52:33,817 --> 01:52:34,517
No, sir.

1505
01:52:36,002 --> 01:52:37,128
What about you?

1506
01:52:37,129 --> 01:52:38,247
Are you blind?

1507
01:52:39,048 --> 01:52:41,174
- Tell me what this is.
- Last night's count.

1508
01:52:41,675 --> 01:52:45,053
You see Dufresne's name there?
I sure do. See? Right there.

1509
01:52:45,054 --> 01:52:46,409
Dufresne.

1510
01:52:48,182 --> 01:52:50,332
He was in his cell at lights out.

1511
01:52:50,533 --> 01:52:53,224
It stands to reason he'd
still be here in the morning.

1512
01:52:54,229 --> 01:52:55,789
I want him found.

1513
01:52:56,190 --> 01:52:59,859
Not tomorrow, not after breakfast. Now!

1514
01:52:59,902 --> 01:53:00,882
Yes, sir!

1515
01:53:02,529 --> 01:53:04,994
Let's go, let's go!
Move your butts! Move it!

1516
01:53:07,951 --> 01:53:08,873
Stand.

1517
01:53:10,120 --> 01:53:11,251
Well?

1518
01:53:14,750 --> 01:53:15,958
Well, what?

1519
01:53:15,959 --> 01:53:19,300
I see you two all the time.
You're thick as thieves, you are.

1520
01:53:20,464 --> 01:53:22,473
He must have said something.

1521
01:53:22,574 --> 01:53:24,100
No, sir, Warden.

1522
01:53:24,401 --> 01:53:25,840
Not a word.

1523
01:53:27,463 --> 01:53:29,944
Lord, it's a miracle!

1524
01:53:30,608 --> 01:53:33,451
A man up and vanished
like a fart in the wind.

1525
01:53:33,752 --> 01:53:35,386
Nothing left but...

1526
01:53:35,787 --> 01:53:38,289
some damn rocks on a windowsill.

1527
01:53:38,590 --> 01:53:41,734
And that cupcake on
the wall. Let's ask her.

1528
01:53:41,735 --> 01:53:46,277
Maybe she knows. What say there,
Fuzzy Britches? Feel like talking?

1529
01:53:46,782 --> 01:53:49,109
Ah... I guess not.

1530
01:53:49,510 --> 01:53:51,670
Why should she be any different?

1531
01:53:53,071 --> 01:53:54,914
This is a conspiracy.

1532
01:53:55,315 --> 01:53:56,808
That's what this is.

1533
01:53:57,409 --> 01:53:59,535
One... big...

1534
01:53:59,936 --> 01:54:01,671
damn conspiracy!

1535
01:54:01,672 --> 01:54:03,424
And everyone's in on it!

1536
01:54:04,125 --> 01:54:05,997
Including her!

1537
01:54:40,377 --> 01:54:42,336
<i>In 1966,</i>

1538
01:54:42,337 --> 01:54:46,355
<i>Andy Dufresne escaped
from Shawshank Prison.</i>

1539
01:54:48,744 --> 01:54:52,079
<i>All they found of him
was a muddy set of prison clothes,</i>

1540
01:54:52,080 --> 01:54:53,806
<i>a bar of soap</i>

1541
01:54:53,807 --> 01:54:58,066
<i>and an old rock hammer
damn near worn down to the nub.</i>

1542
01:55:02,466 --> 01:55:07,387
<i>I remember thinking it would take a man
600 years to tunnel through the wall with it.</i>

1543
01:55:07,688 --> 01:55:10,578
<i>Old Andy did it in less than 20.</i>

1544
01:55:28,759 --> 01:55:30,723
<i>Oh, Andy loved geology.</i>

1545
01:55:31,887 --> 01:55:34,773
<i>I imagine it appealed to
his meticulous nature.</i>

1546
01:55:35,474 --> 01:55:37,250
<i>An Ice Age here,</i>

1547
01:55:37,751 --> 01:55:39,916
<i>a million years of mountain-building there.</i>

1548
01:55:41,280 --> 01:55:44,178
<i>Geology is the study of pressure and time.</i>

1549
01:55:44,908 --> 01:55:46,835
<i>That's all it takes, really.</i>

1550
01:55:47,736 --> 01:55:48,862
<i>Pressure...</i>

1551
01:55:49,263 --> 01:55:50,822
<i>and time.</i>

1552
01:55:51,823 --> 01:55:54,539
<i>That and a big goddamn poster.</i>

1553
01:55:57,871 --> 01:55:59,247
<i>Like I said,</i>

1554
01:55:59,548 --> 01:56:03,222
<i>in prison, a man will do most anything
to keep his mind occupied.</i>

1555
01:56:06,138 --> 01:56:11,292
<i>It turns out Andy's favorite hobby was
toting his wall out into the exercise yard.</i>

1556
01:56:11,393 --> 01:56:13,457
<i>A handful at a time.</i>

1557
01:56:14,913 --> 01:56:16,965
<i>I guess after Tommy was killed,</i>

1558
01:56:17,266 --> 01:56:20,284
<i>Andy decided he'd been here
just about long enough.</i>

1559
01:56:20,285 --> 01:56:22,675
Lickety-split.
I want to get home.

1560
01:56:23,589 --> 01:56:25,653
I'm just about finished, sir.

1561
01:56:46,970 --> 01:56:48,935
Three deposits tonight.

1562
01:56:56,430 --> 01:56:58,352
<i>Andy did like he was told.</i>

1563
01:56:59,016 --> 01:57:02,199
<i>Buffed those shoes
to a high mirror shine.</i>

1564
01:57:06,107 --> 01:57:08,033
<i>The guard simply didn't notice.</i>

1565
01:57:08,634 --> 01:57:09,860
<i>Neither did I.</i>

1566
01:57:10,361 --> 01:57:15,077
<i>I mean, seriously, how often
do you really look at a man's shoes?</i>

1567
01:59:18,739 --> 01:59:24,994
<i>Andy crawled to freedom through 500 yards
of shit-smelling foulness I can't even imagine.</i>

1568
01:59:26,547 --> 01:59:28,831
<i>Or maybe I just don't want to.</i>

1569
01:59:33,062 --> 01:59:35,551
<i>500 yards.</i>

1570
01:59:36,015 --> 01:59:39,096
<i>That's the length
of five football fields.</i>

1571
01:59:39,660 --> 01:59:42,391
<i>Just shy of half a mile.</i>

1572
02:00:37,534 --> 02:00:42,363
<i>The next morning, right about the time
Raquel was spilling her little secret,</i>

1573
02:00:42,764 --> 02:00:45,366
<i>a man nobody ever laid eyes on before</i>

1574
02:00:45,567 --> 02:00:48,169
<i>strode into the Maine National Bank.</i>

1575
02:00:48,570 --> 02:00:50,096
<i>Until that moment,</i>

1576
02:00:50,297 --> 02:00:51,956
<i>he didn't exist,</i>

1577
02:00:52,257 --> 02:00:55,100
<i>- except on paper.
- May I help you?</i>

1578
02:00:55,101 --> 02:00:57,128
<i>He had all the proper ID,</i>

1579
02:00:57,229 --> 02:01:01,040
<i>driver's license, birth certificate,
social security card.</i>

1580
02:01:01,241 --> 02:01:04,218
<i>And the signature was a spot-on match.</i>

1581
02:01:04,269 --> 02:01:07,646
<i>I must say, I'm sorry to
be losing your business.</i>

1582
02:01:07,647 --> 02:01:09,531
I hope you'll enjoy living abroad.

1583
02:01:09,732 --> 02:01:11,208
Thank you.

1584
02:01:11,609 --> 02:01:13,385
I'm sure I will.

1585
02:01:13,686 --> 02:01:15,496
Here's your cashier's check, sir.

1586
02:01:15,597 --> 02:01:17,023
Will there be anything else?

1587
02:01:17,424 --> 02:01:18,224
Please...

1588
02:01:18,808 --> 02:01:21,077
Would you add this
to your outgoing mail?

1589
02:01:21,678 --> 02:01:23,371
I'd be happy to.

1590
02:01:24,872 --> 02:01:26,690
- Good day, sir.
- Good day.

1591
02:01:27,291 --> 02:01:31,467
<i>Mr. Stevens visited nearly a dozen
banks in the Portland area that morning.</i>

1592
02:01:32,255 --> 02:01:38,903
<i>All told, he blew town with better than
$370,000 of Warden Norton's money.</i>

1593
02:01:39,304 --> 02:01:43,312
<i>Severance pay for 19 years.</i>

1594
02:01:49,398 --> 02:01:52,071
Good morning,
Portland Daily Bugle.

1595
02:02:44,411 --> 02:02:47,596
Byron Hadley? You have
the right to remain silent.

1596
02:02:47,597 --> 02:02:49,223
If you give up
the right to remain silent,...

1597
02:02:49,224 --> 02:02:52,609
...anything you say will be held
against you in court of law.

1598
02:02:52,710 --> 02:02:54,170
<i>I wasn't there to see it.</i>

1599
02:02:54,171 --> 02:02:58,430
<i>But I hear Byron Hadley started sobbing
like a little girl when they took him away.</i>

1600
02:03:04,673 --> 02:03:07,946
<i>Norton had no intention
of going that quietly.</i>

1601
02:03:24,041 --> 02:03:25,274
Samuel Norton?

1602
02:03:25,375 --> 02:03:28,217
<i>We have a warrant
for your arrest. Open up.</i>

1603
02:03:31,516 --> 02:03:32,124
Norton!

1604
02:03:32,625 --> 02:03:33,276
Open the door.

1605
02:03:33,877 --> 02:03:35,808
I'm not sure which key it is.

1606
02:03:38,507 --> 02:03:39,454
Norton!

1607
02:03:45,539 --> 02:03:47,203
<i>Make it easy on yourself, Norton.</i>

1608
02:03:59,327 --> 02:04:02,596
<i>I like to think the last
thing that went through his head,</i>

1609
02:04:02,897 --> 02:04:04,490
<i>other than that bullet,</i>

1610
02:04:04,691 --> 02:04:08,974
<i>was to wonder how the hell Andy
Dufresne ever got the best of him.</i>

1611
02:04:10,163 --> 02:04:11,730
Carter, James...

1612
02:04:11,731 --> 02:04:15,092
<i>Not long after the Warden
deprived us of his company,</i>

1613
02:04:15,393 --> 02:04:17,324
<i>I got a postcard in the mail.</i>

1614
02:04:18,555 --> 02:04:21,757
<i>It was blank, but the postmark said...</i>

1615
02:04:21,758 --> 02:04:23,893
<i>Fort Hancock, Texas.</i>

1616
02:04:24,494 --> 02:04:25,720
<i>Fort Hancock.</i>

1617
02:04:26,221 --> 02:04:27,847
<i>Right on the border.</i>

1618
02:04:28,348 --> 02:04:30,174
<i>That's where Andy crossed.</i>

1619
02:04:30,675 --> 02:04:34,733
<i>When I picture him heading south
in his own car with the top down,</i>

1620
02:04:35,297 --> 02:04:37,761
<i>it always makes me laugh.</i>

1621
02:04:39,500 --> 02:04:41,126
<i>Andy Dufresne,</i>

1622
02:04:41,527 --> 02:04:45,753
<i>who crawled through a river of shit
and came out clean on the other side.</i>

1623
02:04:46,783 --> 02:04:48,409
<i>Andy Dufresne,</i>

1624
02:04:48,910 --> 02:04:50,508
<i>headed for the Pacific.</i>

1625
02:04:53,415 --> 02:04:55,941
Hadley's got him by the toes, right?

1626
02:04:56,042 --> 02:04:59,837
And he says, "I believe this boy's
about to have himself an accident."

1627
02:04:59,838 --> 02:05:02,690
<i>Those of us who knew him best
talk about him often.</i>

1628
02:05:03,491 --> 02:05:05,426
<i>I swear, the stuff he pulled...</i>

1629
02:05:05,427 --> 02:05:08,012
"These friends of mine
could use a couple of beers!"

1630
02:05:08,013 --> 02:05:09,977
- And he got it.
- And he got it!

1631
02:05:11,566 --> 02:05:14,026
<i>Sometimes it makes me sad, though,</i>

1632
02:05:14,227 --> 02:05:15,953
<i>Andy being gone.</i>

1633
02:05:16,254 --> 02:05:19,937
<i>I have to remind myself that some
birds aren't meant to be caged.</i>

1634
02:05:21,142 --> 02:05:22,907
<i>Their feathers are just too bright.</i>

1635
02:05:24,671 --> 02:05:26,797
<i>And when they fly away,</i>

1636
02:05:26,898 --> 02:05:31,198
<i>the part of you that knows it was
a sin to lock them up does rejoice.</i>

1637
02:05:32,370 --> 02:05:33,813
<i>But still...</i>

1638
02:05:34,014 --> 02:05:38,163
<i>the place you live in is that much more
drab and empty that they're gone.</i>

1639
02:05:42,631 --> 02:05:45,062
<i>I guess I just miss my friend.</i>

1640
02:06:09,665 --> 02:06:11,021
Please sit down.

1641
02:06:16,531 --> 02:06:18,140
Ellis Boyd Redding.

1642
02:06:18,541 --> 02:06:22,002
Your files say you've served
40 years of a life sentence.

1643
02:06:22,603 --> 02:06:24,560
Do you feel you've been rehabilitated?

1644
02:06:26,808 --> 02:06:28,072
Rehabilitated?

1645
02:06:30,336 --> 02:06:32,101
Well, now, let me see.

1646
02:06:33,265 --> 02:06:35,879
You know, I don't have
any idea what that means.

1647
02:06:37,794 --> 02:06:40,420
Well, it means you're
ready to rejoin society...

1648
02:06:40,421 --> 02:06:42,944
I know what you think it means, sonny.

1649
02:06:44,943 --> 02:06:47,107
To me, it's just a made-up word.

1650
02:06:48,271 --> 02:06:50,506
A politician's word so that...

1651
02:06:51,207 --> 02:06:56,291
young fellas like yourself can wear
a suit and a tie and... have a job.

1652
02:06:58,731 --> 02:07:00,496
What do you really want to know?

1653
02:07:01,584 --> 02:07:03,585
Am I sorry for what I did?

1654
02:07:03,986 --> 02:07:05,176
Well, are you?

1655
02:07:07,023 --> 02:07:09,888
There's not a day
goes by I don't feel regret.

1656
02:07:11,094 --> 02:07:14,801
Not because I'm in here
or because you think I should.

1657
02:07:18,018 --> 02:07:20,982
I look back on the way I was then.

1658
02:07:22,689 --> 02:07:24,315
A young...

1659
02:07:25,116 --> 02:07:28,181
stupid kid who
committed that terrible crime.

1660
02:07:31,640 --> 02:07:33,304
I wanna talk to him.

1661
02:07:35,201 --> 02:07:37,749
I wanna try and talk some sense to him,

1662
02:07:38,413 --> 02:07:40,377
tell him the way things are.

1663
02:07:42,567 --> 02:07:43,832
But I can't.

1664
02:07:46,062 --> 02:07:47,927
That kid's long gone.

1665
02:07:49,341 --> 02:07:51,705
This old man is all that's left.

1666
02:07:53,353 --> 02:07:55,134
I gotta live with that.

1667
02:07:56,389 --> 02:08:00,351
Rehabilitated?
It's just a bullshit word.

1668
02:08:01,252 --> 02:08:06,153
So you go on and stamp your form,
sonny, and stop wasting my time.

1669
02:08:07,259 --> 02:08:09,085
Because to tell you the truth,

1670
02:08:09,686 --> 02:08:11,667
I don't give a shit.

1671
02:09:38,139 --> 02:09:39,664
Here you go, miss.

1672
02:09:42,487 --> 02:09:44,125
Rest room break, boss?

1673
02:09:49,794 --> 02:09:54,269
You don't need to ask me every time you
need to go take a piss. Just go. Understand?

1674
02:09:55,300 --> 02:09:56,447
Yes, sir.

1675
02:10:07,020 --> 02:10:09,943
<i>40 years I've been
asking permission to piss.</i>

1676
02:10:11,065 --> 02:10:13,955
<i>I can't squeeze a drop without say-so.</i>

1677
02:10:17,805 --> 02:10:19,670
<i>There's a harsh truth to face.</i>

1678
02:10:21,451 --> 02:10:23,965
<i>No way I'm gonna make it on the outside.</i>

1679
02:10:32,303 --> 02:10:36,044
<i>All I do any more is think
of ways to break my parole...</i>

1680
02:10:36,808 --> 02:10:39,072
<i>...so maybe they'd send me back.</i>

1681
02:10:44,398 --> 02:10:46,863
<i>A terrible thing to live in fear.</i>

1682
02:10:47,660 --> 02:10:51,518
<i>Brooks Hatlen knew it,
knew it all too well.</i>

1683
02:10:53,107 --> 02:10:56,381
<i>All I want is to be back
where things make sense,</i>

1684
02:10:56,945 --> 02:10:59,826
<i>where I won't have to
be afraid all the time.</i>

1685
02:11:01,825 --> 02:11:03,989
<i>Only one thing stops me.</i>

1686
02:11:05,353 --> 02:11:07,618
<i>A promise I made to Andy.</i>

1687
02:11:28,268 --> 02:11:29,532
Here it is.

1688
02:11:40,154 --> 02:11:41,819
Much obliged, sir.

1689
02:15:21,042 --> 02:15:22,417
<i>Dear Red,</i>

1690
02:15:22,418 --> 02:15:24,961
<i>if you're reading this, you've gotten out.</i>

1691
02:15:25,162 --> 02:15:29,099
<i>And if you've come this far, maybe
you're willing to come a little further.</i>

1692
02:15:29,600 --> 02:15:32,065
<i>You remember the name
of the town, don't you?</i>

1693
02:15:34,180 --> 02:15:36,144
Zihuatanejo.

1694
02:15:37,408 --> 02:15:40,727
<i>I could use a good man to help
me get my project on wheels.</i>

1695
02:15:41,528 --> 02:15:45,161
<i>I'll keep an eye out for you
and the chessboard ready.</i>

1696
02:15:46,025 --> 02:15:47,184
<i>Remember, Red,</i>

1697
02:15:47,485 --> 02:15:50,011
<i>hope is a good thing.</i>

1698
02:15:50,112 --> 02:15:51,938
<i>Maybe the best of things.</i>

1699
02:15:52,139 --> 02:15:54,204
<i>And no good thing ever dies.</i>

1700
02:15:54,867 --> 02:15:57,810
<i>I will be hoping that
this letter finds you</i>

1701
02:15:57,911 --> 02:15:59,538
<i>and finds you well.</i>

1702
02:16:00,039 --> 02:16:02,420
<i>Your friend, Andy.</i>

1703
02:16:36,617 --> 02:16:40,375
<i>Get busy living or get busy dying.</i>

1704
02:16:42,999 --> 02:16:44,963
<i>That's goddamn right.</i>

1705
02:16:50,590 --> 02:16:52,799
<i>For the second time in my life,</i>

1706
02:16:52,800 --> 02:16:55,165
<i>I'm guilty of committing a crime.</i>

1707
02:16:56,554 --> 02:16:58,638
<i>Parole violation.</i>

1708
02:16:59,139 --> 02:17:02,830
<i>Of course, I doubt they'll toss up
any roadblocks for that.</i>

1709
02:17:03,703 --> 02:17:05,729
<i>Not for an old crook like me.</i>

1710
02:17:05,930 --> 02:17:07,994
Fort Hancock, Texas, please.

1711
02:17:11,527 --> 02:17:16,235
<i>I find I'm so excited I can barely sit
still or hold a thought in my head.</i>

1712
02:17:16,699 --> 02:17:19,784
<i>I think it's the excitement
only a free man can feel.</i>

1713
02:17:20,265 --> 02:17:25,378
<i>A free man at the start of a long journey
whose conclusion is uncertain.</i>

1714
02:17:28,377 --> 02:17:31,025
<i>I hope I can make it across the border.</i>

1715
02:17:32,523 --> 02:17:35,596
<i>I hope to see my friend
and shake his hand.</i>

1716
02:17:37,595 --> 02:17:41,385
<i>I hope the Pacific is as blue
as it has been in my dreams.</i>

1717
02:17:43,459 --> 02:17:44,915
<i>I hope.</i>
